  &lt;body&gt;
    &lt;font face=&quot;Verdana&quot; size=&quot;2&quot;&gt;The Maxwell speed distribution theorem was 
    derived based on the ideal gas, with the assumption that there are no 
    interactions between the atoms. The reality is that there always exist 
    interatomic interactions (e.g. the van der Waals forces) among atoms. Do 
    they play a role in making the speed distributions? In this activity, you 
    will find out the answer.&lt;br&gt;&lt;br&gt;Please run the simulation until the tape 
    of the recorder is full, stop the simulation, and click the button below 
    the model window. Take a snapshot of the graph. Now, reset the model, 
    adjust the interactions using the two sliders below the model window. 
    Compare the graphs produced at different times, and draw your conclusion. 
    You can compare the take snapshots in the Snapshot Gallery.&lt;/font&gt;
  &lt;/body&gt;
&lt;/html&gt;
</title>
<opaque>false</opaque>
</component></content>

